03984nam a22005175i 9780773564107DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19921992xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735641077 a10.1515/97807735641072doi  a(DE-B1597)654953  a(OCoLC)732601072  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aB693.Z7bS34 1992eb 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a186/.41 aSchroeder, Frederic M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aForm and Transformation :bA Study in the Philosophy of Plotinus /cFrederic M. Schroeder. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1992] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (144 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Ideas ;v1600tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tForm -- tLight -- tSilence -- tWord -- tLove -- tBibliography -- tIndex Locorum -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Platonic Form is often presented as an instrument of explanation and as a cause in ontology, epistemology, and ethics. As such, it is usually approached from the perspective of its relations to the particulars of the sensible world. Frederic Schroeder contends that Plotinus argues for the sovereignty of the Platonic Form both as a ground of being and as an intrinsically valuable object of intellective and spiritual vision. These two aspects coalesce in the thought of Plotinus, for whom the Form is, apart from its philosophical uses, an object of enjoyment. Schroeder argues also that the particular must be seen as having an intrinsic character, distinct from its relationship to the Form or to other particulars. The particular thus becomes a window on the world of Form. In the course of his exploration of the sovereignty of Form, Schroeder examines the themes of illumination, silence, language, and love. He undertakes an immanent interpretation of the Plotinian text, showing how Plotinian vocabulary displays intricate internal connections and genetic relationships. Schroeder shows that Plotinus' thought is not susceptible to organization into a closed, linear synthesis but has its own order, centred on the conviction that Form is of intrinsic value and that it is only from the perspective of this intrinsic value that we can understand its uses and significance in explanation and causation. Rather than trying to construct such a synthesis, Schroeder, starting from this basic insight into Plotinus' understanding of the Platonic Form, leads the reader to a greater understanding of Plotinus' manner of philosophizing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356410740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564107423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773564107/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles